\begin_layout Subsection
Pressure of each fluid
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 assumed that each co-located fluid shared the same pressure, leading to
 unstable equations that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 stabilised using diffusion of vertical velocity and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 stabilised using mass exchanges or drag between the fluids.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 achieved realistic results in single column experiments of convective boundary
 layer but the amount of diffusion needed would spoil simulations in the
 free troposphere.
 The stabilisation used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 meant that the two fluids tended to move as one which defeats the purpose
 of using multi-fluid modelling.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The instabilities reported by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 showed growing divergence in a fluid with vanishing volume fraction.
 This is unsurprising because it is mass convergence rather than velocity
 convergence that leads to pressure spikes that remove the convergence.
 If the volume (or mass) fraction of fluid is vanishingly low then convergence
 cannot lead to a spike in the total pressure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will assume that pressure in each fluid is given by a parameterised perturbat
ion from the total pressure, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{i}=P+p_{i}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BN86"

\end_inset

proposed a parameterisation for pressure differences in a multi-phase explosion
 model that has been widely used in mathematics and engineering for simulating
 fluidised beds of granular material 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "EHM92"

\end_inset

 and two compressible fluids 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "eg."
key "SA99"

\end_inset

.
 In these methods, advection equations are written for the volume fraction,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, and conservation equations are written for mass fraction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 In our notation, ignoring transfers between fluids, these equations would
 be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\partial\sigma_{i}}{\partial t}+\mathbf{V}\cdot\nabla\sigma_{i} & = & \mu\left(P_{i}-P_{j}\right)\\
\frac{\partial\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}}{\partial t}+\nabla\cdot\left(\sigma_{i}\rho_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\right) & = & 0
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the interface between fluids, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the compaction viscosity which controls how quickly the pressure of
 each fluid relaxes to the mean pressure and index 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 refers to the other fluid in a two fluid system.
 In our Boussinesq system 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 does not appear in the continuity equation.
 Different authors make different assumptions about the interface velocity
 but if we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}=\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{i}$
\end_inset

 is constant then we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu p_{i}=-\sigma_{i}^{2}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 If we assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{V}=\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each fluid then we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu p_{i}=-\sigma_{i}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 stabilised the multi-fluid equations by adding a diffusion term 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\partial w^{2}/\partial z^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the RHS of the 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 equation.
 If a fluid perturbation pressure is set to 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nu\partial w/\partial z$
\end_inset

 this is equivalent to the diffusion term in one dimension.
 However addition a diffusion term will harm three dimensional simulations
 are resolved convection in the free troposphere whereas adding a fluid
 perturbation pressure will not.
 We have additional constraints that we want 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}p_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 and we do not want the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla p_{i}$
\end_inset

 to destroy 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\nabla\cdot\sigma_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, inspired by both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BN86"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

 we assume that the pressure in each fluid is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}p_{i}=-\gamma\nabla\cdot\sigma_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}\label{eq:Pi_div}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 is a free coefficient.
 This parameterisation and sensitivity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 will be evaluated in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:results"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Entrainment and Detrainment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider dry air without turbulence so use the dynamic entrainment described
 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HC51,AK67,DBF+13"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{ij}=\begin{cases}
-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i} & \text{if }\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}<0\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

which is necessary to stop air in one fluid from accumulating when vertical
 motion ceases (at the top of a rising plume or at the bottom of descending
 air).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Drag in the Momentum Equation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:drag"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Pressure differences between the fluids can lead to form drag which is parameter
ised following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SW69,RC15,WM19"

\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{D}_{ij}=\frac{\sigma_{j}C_{D}}{r_{c}}|\mathbf{u}_{i}-\mathbf{u}_{j}|\left(\mathbf{u}_{i}-\mathbf{u}_{j}\right)\label{eq:dragBubble}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{D}$
\end_inset

 is a drag coefficient, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a cloud radius.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{c}$
\end_inset

 are defined based on the test cases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Buoyancy and the Momentum of the Mass that is Transferred
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different fluids are not likely to be well mixed and it is assumed that
 the most buoyant air is transferred from fluid 0 to fluid 1 and vice versa
 and that the air with least downward momentum is transferred from 0 to
 1 and vice versa.
 The properties of the fluids transferred should depend on modelling of
 sub-grid-scale variability which is beyond the scope of this paper.
 Conditional averaging of high resolution single fluid solutions depends
 on the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and so it is sensible to assume that the vertical velocity of the fluid
 transferred is zero.
 For two dimensional multi-fluid simulations we assume that the horizontal
 velocity transferred is equal to the mean horizontal velocity of the fluid
 transferred from.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{u}_{ij}^{T}=\begin{pmatrix}u_{i}\\
v_{i}\\
0
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For buoyancy, following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TEB19"

\end_inset

, we use:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{ij}^{T}=\theta_{b}b_{i}+(1-\theta_{b})b_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and present results using 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{b}=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{b}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{b}\ne1$
\end_inset

 implies that the buoyancy of the fluid transferred depends on the properties
 of the receiving fluid which is not logical and can lead to unbounded values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the fluid that is loosing mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Numerical Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spatial discretisation follows exactly 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

, solving advective form equations using monotonic, finite volume advection
 and C-grid, Lorenz staggering.
 The time-stepping is Crank-Nicolson with no off-centering and with deferred
 correction of explicitly solved variables.
 It is different from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 because here we solve the Boussinesq equations and we need stable solutions
 for equations with a separate pressure in each fluid.
 We use two outer iterations per time step to update explicitly solved variables.
 For the first outer iteration, predicted values for time 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 are set to those from time level 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and are given the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 For the second iteration, values at 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 are set to those from the end of the first iteration.
 The implicit numerical method for applying the transfers between fluids
 is specific for two fluids because it involves the inversion of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The prognostic variables are the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 in cell centres, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

 is cell centres and the velocity flux: the velocity at cell faces dotted
 with the area vector for each face (normal to the face), 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}=\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The pressures, 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 are diagnostic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first equation to be solved each outer iteration is eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:sigma"

\end_inset

) for each 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, operator split; first applying advection, then correcting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 and then applying mass transfers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\sigma_{i}^{\prime} & = & \sigma_{i}^{n}-\frac{\Delta t}{2}\nabla\cdot\left\{ \left(\mathbf{u}_{i}^{n}+\mathbf{u}_{i}^{\ell}\right)\left(\sigma_{i}^{n}\right)_{vL}\right\} \\
\sigma_{i}^{\prime\prime} & = & \sigma_{i}^{\prime}\bigg/\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}^{\prime}\\
S_{ij} & = & \begin{cases}
-\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}^{\ell} & \text{if }\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}^{\ell}<0\\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}\\
\sigma_{i}^{n+1} & = & \sigma_{i}^{\prime\prime}+\Delta t\sum_{j\ne i}\sigma_{j}^{\prime\prime}S_{ji}-\sigma_{i}^{\prime\prime}S_{ij}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t$
\end_inset

 is the time step and the superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $\prime$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\prime\prime$
\end_inset

 denote intermediate values.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 is interpolated from cell centres onto cell faces using monotonic van-Leer
 advection (operator 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{i}^{n})_{vL}$
\end_inset

) as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

 using exclusively values at time level 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for best accuracy and guaranteed monotonicity.
 For calculating the divergence, the normal component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is needed at cell faces which are prognostic variables of the C-grid.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are limited to ensure 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\sigma_{i}<1\ \forall i$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:b"

\end_inset

) is solved for the buoyancy in each fluid.
 The transfer terms can be very large so they are treated operator split
 and implicitly, with 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 coming from the solution of a 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 being the back-substitution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
b_{i}^{\prime} & = & b_{i}^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{2}\left(b_{it}^{n}+b_{it}^{\ell}\right)\\
\text{where }b_{it} & = & -\nabla\cdot\left(\mathbf{u}_{i}(b_{i})_{vL}\right)+b_{i}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}-N^{2}w_{i}+\alpha\nabla^{2}b_{i}\\
b_{0}^{n+1} & = & \frac{\left(1+\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{0}}{\sigma_{1}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{01}\right)b_{0}^{\prime}+\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{1}}{\sigma_{0}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{10}b_{1}^{\prime}}{1+\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{0}}{\sigma_{1}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{01}+\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{1}}{\sigma_{0}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{10}}\\
b_{1}^{n+1} & = & \frac{\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{0}}{\sigma_{1}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{01}b_{0}^{n+1}+b_{1}^{\prime}}{1+\Delta t\left(\frac{\sigma_{0}}{\sigma_{1}}\right)^{\prime\prime}S_{01}}.
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The use of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\sigma_{0}/\sigma_{1})^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

 before the mass transfers is necessary to ensure bounded and conservative
 transfers, as described by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
cite{MWH1x}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next a Poisson equation is solved to calculate the total pressure to ensure
 that the total velocity is divergence free.
 The pressure equation also provides updates for the velocity flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 First an intermediate velocity flux is calculated with partial updates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
u_{i}^{\prime}= & u_{i}^{n}+\frac{\Delta t}{2} & \biggl(\left(-\nabla\cdot(\mathbf{u}_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i})+\mathbf{u}_{i}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}+b_{i}\mathbf{k}\right)_{f}^{\ell}\cdot\mathbf{S}-\nabla_{f}p_{i}^{\ell}\\
 &  & +\left(-\nabla\cdot(\mathbf{u}_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i})+\mathbf{u}_{i}\nabla\cdot\mathbf{u}_{i}+b_{i}\mathbf{k}\right)_{f}^{n}\cdot\mathbf{S}-\nabla_{f}(P+p_{i})^{n}\biggr)
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where operator 
\begin_inset Formula $()_{f}$
\end_inset

 means linear interpolation from cell centres onto cell faces and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla_{f}P$
\end_inset

 is a compact discretisation of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\nabla P)_{f}\cdot\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

: ie the normal component of the pressure gradient calculated from just
 the values of pressure either side of the face.
 Once we have calculated 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{n+1}$
\end_inset

, the velocity flux (without momentum transfers) is updated from the back-substi
tution:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
u_{i}^{\prime\prime}=u_{i}^{\prime}-\frac{\Delta t}{2}\nabla_{f}P^{n+1}.\label{eq:backSub}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Poisson equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is found by multiplying each eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:backSub"

\end_inset

) by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, summing over all fluids and taking the divergence.
 Knowing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla\cdot\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}p_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\sum_{i}\sigma_{i}u_{i}^{\prime}-\frac{\Delta t}{2}\nabla^{2}P^{n+1}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is solved to find 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, the momentum transfers due to mass transfer and due to drag are calculated
 implicitly, similar to the implicit transfers of buoyancy, calculating
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{\prime\prime}$
\end_inset

.
 These do not influence the total 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 or total divergence because momentum is transferred conservatively.
 However they do influence 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 which is why they are calculated before 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The final stage of the time step iteration is to solve Helmholtz equations
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sigma_{i}^{n+1}p_{i}^{n+1}=-\gamma\nabla\cdot\left(\sigma_{if}^{n+1}u_{i}^{n+1}-\frac{\Delta t}{2}\sigma_{if}^{n+1}\nabla_{f}\left(p_{i}^{n+1}-p_{i}^{\ell}\right)\right).\label{eq:pi_Helm}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Both 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 appear in eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:pi_Helm"

\end_inset

) because 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 already contains contributions from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\ell}$
\end_inset

 so these are removed before updating 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 No back substitution for 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 is done after calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 because this would destroy the divergence free constraint.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

 only satisfies eqn (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Pi_div"

\end_inset

) exactly if the outer iterations converge and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}^{\ell}=p_{i}^{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final stage of the time step iteration is to reconstruct 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is from 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "WM19"

\end_inset

.
 The stages calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are repeated twice per time step iteration.
 The Poisson and Helmholtz equations are solved to a tolerance of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{-6}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

